defaultLONDON CHALLENGEdefault&#xa0;defaultThe NUT believes that the London Challenge provides an example of a sustainable 
defaultapproach to 
defaultschool improvement 
defaultthat has resulted in the capital’s schools, one suffering a poor reputation, being highly regarded and a model for others. The NUT 
defaulthas 
defaultset out 
defaultits case in its 
defaultevidence to 
defaultthe 
defaultEducation Committee Inquiry into ‘School Partnerships and Cooperation
default. 
defaultA summary of the record of the challenge by the DfE Evaluation Report’s lead author is also available on the NUT website.
default&#xa0;
defaultLondon Challenge was not only
default highly successful; it was also, unlike the academies programme, extremely cost effective. O
defaultver three years the funding for City Challenge was £160 million, considerably cheaper than the £8.5 billion reportedly spent on the academies programme over two yea
defaultrs.
default&#xa0;
defaultIgnoring cost-effective school improvement options and promoting costly and contentious one
defaults
default should not be countenanced by Ministers at a time when budgets are under pressure.
default&#xa0;defaultFREE SCHOOLSdefault&#xa0;defaultThe NUT believes that the process for approving and 
defaultestablishing free schools lacks transparency, ignores the evidence on the need for new school places locally and fails to take account of the impact of free schools on neighbouring schools.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe NUT’s 
defaultevidence to support this view are set out 
defaultits recently 
defaultpublished document, ’Free Schools, Free for All’
default which is available 
defaulton the NUT’s website.
